DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(91)90038-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199691900388
AB  - This paper explores the role of R&D subsidies in the presence of incomplete information. We consider a market for ‘experience goods’, where a firm's R&D investment determines the quality of its product but where quality becomes observable to consumers only through experience with the product. In this model, externalities emerge in that individual firms cannot fully appropriate the benefits of their quality-enhancing investment outlays. We show that an R&D subsidy can internalize this externality, and characterize optimal infant industry intervention in this setting.
