AB  - Import duties and inflation taxes generate significant tax revenues for many developing nations. These taxes involve low collection costs relative to income taxes and generate distinct types of distortions, so their use can be reconciled with Ramsey taxation principles. A small open overlapping generations economy is presented in which optimal tariffs and inflation taxes are positive, both when home currency has no good substitutes and when inflation gives rise to currency substitution. Compared with a regime of tariffs and direct taxes on foreign assets, welfare is lower in the optimal inflation-tariff equilibrium.
